00:01:24.320 --> 00:01:30.000
And so one of the questions that was asked a bit earlier during the demo, which I thought

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:35.919
might be helpful to cover is, what exactly does pinning data mean?

00:01:35.919 --> 00:01:38.279
Yeah, and I can take this one.

00:01:38.279 --> 00:01:41.559
So pins is something I use all the time.

00:01:41.559 --> 00:01:45.720
And the way I like to think of it and kind of the way the package is named, pins, I think

00:01:45.720 --> 00:01:48.160
of it like a sticky note or a piece of paper.

00:01:48.160 --> 00:01:52.519
You walk into your office and you pin that sticky note or piece of paper to a board on

00:01:52.519 --> 00:01:53.519
your office.

00:01:53.720 --> 00:01:57.559
And then your colleagues can walk by, they can see that piece of paper, they can interact

00:01:57.559 --> 00:01:59.959
with it, they can use that piece of paper.

00:01:59.959 --> 00:02:04.559
So it's a great way to take any object you've created in R, that could be a data set like

00:02:04.559 --> 00:02:05.559
we did today.

00:02:05.559 --> 00:02:08.759
It could also be a model, any other R object.

00:02:08.759 --> 00:02:10.119
You can also do this in Python.

00:02:10.119 --> 00:02:13.399
So definitely if you're a Python developer, you can still pin data.

00:02:13.399 --> 00:02:17.399
And it allows you to take that data and pin it to a location, a board.

00:02:17.399 --> 00:02:18.839
That can be Connect, like we did today.

00:02:19.039 --> 00:02:20.800
It could be another location.

00:02:20.800 --> 00:02:25.639
And it allows your other, your future self, any of your colleagues to incorporate that

00:02:25.639 --> 00:02:28.160
pin data set into their workflows.

00:02:28.160 --> 00:02:32.559
So rather than, for example, maybe you have a Shiny application, and if you're deploying

00:02:32.559 --> 00:02:38.160
it to Connect, you might have to kind of include that data with the application, that bundle.

00:02:38.160 --> 00:02:42.279
But if you use pins, you can just publish just the code and the Shiny application can

00:02:42.279 --> 00:02:46.679
reach out to that pin and pull it in automatically, so you don't have to kind of attach that data

00:02:46.679 --> 00:02:48.600
set to the application itself.

00:02:48.600 --> 00:02:50.479
Yeah, pins is great.

00:02:50.479 --> 00:02:53.520
It's a really good tool for building out some powerful workflows.

00:02:53.520 --> 00:02:56.679
