00:12:07.820 --> 00:12:13.859
It looks like there's some questions about comparing Quarto to R Markdown, especially

00:12:13.859 --> 00:12:15.900
if you're an R developer.

00:12:15.900 --> 00:12:21.619
So just to reiterate from the YouTube channel comments, there was questions of like, is

00:12:21.619 --> 00:12:23.500
R Markdown going away?

00:12:23.500 --> 00:12:26.460
No, we are still supporting R Markdown.

00:12:26.460 --> 00:12:29.020
That will be continued support.

00:12:29.020 --> 00:12:33.700
Quarto, I think the advantage there is that there are additional features.

00:12:33.700 --> 00:12:40.940
It is easier to switch what that output looks like, whether it be a slide or a report, even

00:12:40.940 --> 00:12:47.219
dynamic content or PDF, Word docs, even Confluence now.

00:12:47.219 --> 00:12:54.299
So there's a lot of additional features that are in Quarto on top of being able to very

00:12:54.299 --> 00:13:00.140
easily work with Python or other languages that you might experience.

00:13:00.140 --> 00:13:07.700
And that way you're a little bit more in a non-R centric platform, whereas R Markdown

00:13:07.700 --> 00:13:10.460
has to run within an R environment.

00:13:10.460 --> 00:13:14.460
Quarto runs outside of an R environment that can run R within it.

00:13:14.460 --> 00:13:19.979
So there's a little bit of technicality there, but I think that does open the door for those

00:13:19.979 --> 00:13:22.580
multilingual teams that we do see.

00:13:22.580 --> 00:13:23.580
Yeah.

00:13:23.580 --> 00:13:28.500
And to add on that as well, like, you know, in a lot of ways you can think of Quarto as

00:13:28.500 --> 00:13:33.700
like R Markdown 2.0, but it is our way of bringing R Markdown essentially to anyone.

00:13:33.700 --> 00:13:39.659
If you're a Python developer, if you're a Julia developer, if you're an observable developer,

00:13:39.659 --> 00:13:41.940
you can create a Quarto document.

00:13:41.940 --> 00:13:47.059
And one of my coolest things about Quarto is that the way it's designed, it's actually

00:13:47.059 --> 00:13:51.020
can support data science languages that may not even exist today.

00:13:51.020 --> 00:13:56.940
So in 10, 20, 50, a hundred years from now, the landscape of data science could look completely

00:13:56.940 --> 00:13:57.940
different.

00:13:57.940 --> 00:14:00.780
There could be new languages that are at that forefront of data science.

00:14:00.780 --> 00:14:04.619
And we expect Quarto to be around during that time, can easily work with these languages

00:14:04.619 --> 00:14:05.619
as well.

00:14:05.619 --> 00:14:10.340
Thank you so much.

